Based on the image provided, you are looking at Supreme Commander: Forged Alliance (or the original Supreme Commander). It is worth noting that while there isn't an official game called "Supreme Commander Reforged," you are likely thinking of the Forged Alliance Forever (FAF) community project, which keeps the game alive with updated shaders, textures, and lighting that give it a "reforged" look.

Here is a breakdown of the art style and the technical research on how Gas Powered Games (and the community) achieved this look.

1. The Art Style: "Scale over Detail"
The defining characteristic of Supreme Commander’s art direction is readability at infinite scale. The game was designed around the "Strategic Zoom" feature, meaning the art had to look good from 10 feet away and 10 kilometers up.

Utilitarian & Faction-Specific: Because you view units from far away, the art team relied on distinct silhouettes rather than tiny details to distinguish factions.

UEF (United Earth Federation): Blocky, industrial, utilitarian, tank-treads. Textures are matte camo and heavy metals.

Cybran Nation (seen in your image): Angular, insectoid, sharp edges. The "Spider Bot" (Megalith) in your image is the prime example—lots of red glowing lights and jagged, stealth-fighter geometry.

Aeon Illuminate: Smooth, flowing curves, floating units, white and gold ceramics.

Seraphim: Asymmetrical, ethereal, organic alien shapes.

Ballistic Visuals: Unlike other RTS games where lasers instantly hit (hitscan), SupCom simulates every projectile. The art style emphasizes tracers, smoke trails, and firing arcs so you can visually track the flow of battle from a zoomed-out view.

2. How They Made It (Technical Research)
The game runs on the Moho Engine, custom-built by Gas Powered Games (Chris Taylor’s team) specifically to handle this "Zoom from a single unit to the whole planet" mechanic. Here is how they pulled it off:

A. The LOD (Level of Detail) & Imposter System
This is the "secret sauce" of Supreme Commander.

The Problem: Rendering 1,000 units at full detail would melt any computer (especially in 2007).

The Solution: They used an aggressive 3-stage visual system.

Close Range: You see the full 3D model with high-res textures and normal maps.

Mid Range: The game swaps the model for a "Low Poly" version with simplified geometry.

Far Range (Imposters): This is the genius part. When you zoom out, the 3D units are replaced by 2D sprites (billboards) that always face the camera. These are pre-rendered images of the units.

Strategic View: Finally, at max zoom, they turn into Strategic Icons (the little geometric shapes).

Effect: This allows the engine to render massive armies without processing millions of polygons.

B. Texture Splatting & Normal Mapping
Terrain: The ground isn't just one big texture. They used Texture Splatting, where they layer multiple textures (sand, rock, grass) and blend them using an "alpha map" to create natural transitions without hard edges.

Normal Maps: To make the flat surfaces of the tanks look detailed, they relied heavily on "Normal Maps" (blue/purple textures that tell the light how to bounce). This makes a flat grey polygon look like it has bolts, vents, and panels without actually adding extra 3D geometry.

C. Lighting (Spherical Harmonics)
The lighting in your image (the bright laser beam and the shadows) uses a technique called Light Space Perspective Shadow Maps (LiSPSM). This concentrates shadow resolution near the camera, so shadows look crisp close up but get blurry far away (where you can't see them anyway).

They also used Spherical Harmonic Lighting for the ambient light, which allowed units to look grounded in the environment (e.g., reflecting the green of the grass on their undersides).

D. The "Reforged" Look (FAF Community Updates)
If you are playing via Forged Alliance Forever (FAF), the community has actually patched the rendering engine.

New Shaders: They added better water reflections and sharper shadows.

Texture Upscaling: Some modders use AI upscaling to sharpen the original 2007 textures for 4K monitors.

Lighting Fixes: They fixed bugs in the original engine that caused lighting to look flat on certain maps.

One Next Step: If you want to see exactly how the "Imposter" system works, I can guide you on how to activate the debug view in the game, which turns on wireframes so you can see the exact moment the 3D models swap to 2D sprites. Would you like to know the console command for that?

